n        left = 0\n        max_length = 0\n        zeros_count = 0\n        \n        for right in range(len(nums)):\n            if nums[right] == 0:\n                zeros_count += 1\n            \n            while zeros_count > k:\n                if nums[left] == 0:\n                    zeros_count -= 1\n                left += 1\n            \n            max_length = max(max_length, right - left + 1)\n        \n        return max_length\n```\n\nThis solution uses a sliding window approach to find the maximum number of consecutive 1's in the array, allowing up to `k` 0's to be flipped. The `left` and `right` pointers define the current window, and `zeros_count` keeps track of the number of 0's in the current window. If `zeros_count` exceeds `k`, the window is shrunk from the left until `zeros_count` is at most `k`. The maximum length of such a window is tracked and returned.", "estimated_date": 1551571200000}